result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

14CF240, 14TR3731, 14TR3732, 14TR3733, 15CF157 & 15CF254 - Defendant Logan G. Breselow in court with attorney Jacquelyn Wolter.  James T. Sempf appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court questions def and reviews chgs and pens.  NC plea entered in Count 1 of 14CF240 and NC plea entered in Count 1 of 15CF157.  Court accepts pleas and finds def guilty.  All remaining charges are DRI.  State heard on sentencing recomendations.  Atty Wolter responds.   Court heard and imposes sentence as follows:

14CF240:
w/held sentence
2 yrs probation
180 days DCJ w/h&t comm.  on or before 9/30/15
Court costs
AODA
Maintain absolute sobriety
No bars
VIP
No operation of motor vehicle w/o valid DL

15CF157:
$1,000 fine + court costs

Defendant may request expungement upon successful completion of probation

Defendant shall not consume alcohol or other intoxicants.  Defendant must maintain absolute sobriety.  and shall not go upon the premises of any establishment whose primary business activity involves the sale or distribution of alcoholic beverages, including bars, taverns, liquor stores and beer tents.  Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle unless he has a valid Wisconsin driver's license. Defendant shall not leave the State of Wisconsin.

12:56 - Defendant Logan G. Breselow in court, in custody with attorney Jacquelyn Wolter. Intern Kevin Schmidt in person w/ADA Gilbert Grant Thompson by phone for the State of Wisconsin.   Defendant has received copy of Criminal Complaint and advised of rights, charges, penalties and right to Preliminary Hearing. Court finds probable cause. Prelim requested, waiving time limits. Prelim set. Court sets $5000 PA bond with conditions:   Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle unless he has a valid Wisconsin driver's license.  Defendant shall not consume alcohol or other intoxicants.  Defendant must maintain absolute sobriety and shall not go upon the premises of any establishment whose primary business activity involves the sale or distribution of alcoholic beverages, including bars, taverns, liquor stores and beer tents. Defendant shall not leave the State of Wisconsin.  Preliminary hearing scheduled for September 3, 2015 at 08:30 am.
